    <item>
      <title>Setup Guide For Love2D And Visual Studio Code (Windows)</title>
      <link>https://gabejstein.github.io/tutorial/love2d-vs-code-setup/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 02 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://gabejstein.github.io/tutorial/love2d-vs-code-setup/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A lot of people have asked me how I set up Visual Studio Code to work with Love2D. The video below will show you how I set it up, but it&amp;rsquo;s not necessarily the only way to do it. With this setup you get Lua syntax highlighting, code auto-complete and the ability to use Love from the console without having to enter the full program path.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;It also shows how to download and install Love.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Using The Push Library With Love2D</title>
      <link>https://gabejstein.github.io/tutorial/love2d-push-library/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 02 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://gabejstein.github.io/tutorial/love2d-push-library/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;There&amp;rsquo;s a good chance that you&amp;rsquo;ll make a game and won&amp;rsquo;t even know what screen size your player will have. This can make it difficult to design things like user interfaces, sprite sizes, etc. There are many ways to deal with this problem, but I think the simplest thing is to draw to a render texture at a fixed size and have that scale automatically to fit any screen.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I think the Push library is great for handling that, and it&amp;rsquo;s excellent for making games with pixel art as well. The video below is quick guide to setting it up.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>About Gabe</title>
      <link>https://gabejstein.github.io/page/about/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://gabejstein.github.io/page/about/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://gabejstein.github.io/images/gabe_icecream.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;Gabe Stein&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Gabe is the founder of &lt;strong&gt;Studio Boshi&lt;/strong&gt; and the &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.youtube.com/@GabeStein&#34;&gt;Gabe Stein Youtube Channel&lt;/a&gt;, where he teaches game programming concepts and related things. Most of his games are made without engines and he likes to code at a low level using languages like C. He&amp;rsquo;s also been a big proponent of Lua.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;He lived in Kawasaki, Japan for 9 years before moving back to his hometown of Toronto, Canada. He&amp;rsquo;s currently developing &lt;a href=&#34;https://store.steampowered.com/app/3605940/Ocean_City_Killer/?beta=0&#34;&gt;Ocean City Killer&lt;/a&gt;, a retro cyberpunk adventure. He enjoys cycling, photography, and sketching.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Game Objects and Inheritance in Lua</title>
      <link>https://gabejstein.github.io/tutorial/love2d-inheritance/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://gabejstein.github.io/tutorial/love2d-inheritance/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Some people think that inheritance is impossible in Lua. It&amp;rsquo;s not a built-in feature of the language like in C++ or Java, but there&amp;rsquo;s still a way to fake it with meta-tables. This video shows one way to do it and how it can allow you to create a variety of game objects without having to rewrite a lot of code.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;This video was originally published on October 30, 2024.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
